they would support or replace the company's senior management, including its chairman and chief executive, Franklin D. Raines, and its chief financial officer, J. Timothy Howard.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="11,13,21,22,23,41,55"><scu uid="2" label="The Dec. 19 meeting concluded without any announcement of a decision" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>After the Securities and Exchange Commission said it had agreed with OFHEO that Fannie had misrepresented its financial position, the board chose to act more deliberately to make sure the decisions it made were the right ones, the spokesman said.</line><line>Another recipient of Fannie Mae Foundation grants -- $125,000 since 1993 -- is the Federal City Council, a nonprofit organization based in Washington that works to improve the city.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Mudd joined Fannie Mae in February 2000 after nearly a decade at GE Capital, where he rose through the management ranks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Raines, 55, a former budget director under President Clinton, has long held himself up as a paragon of corporate ethics.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="23,31"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>But the most important response to Fannie Mae's humiliation goes beyond punishment of individuals.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>The board had come under heavy criticism in recent weeks for allowing both men to leave the company with lucrative severance packages.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>It's time to invigorate it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Here's the question: Just how independent are Fannie Mae's independent directors?</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>Howard could be eligible for 84,000 dollars in salary between December 20 and the end of January 2005, before claiming 36,000 dollars a month once retired.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>It was hard to know whom to believe.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>He knows his stuff.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Derivatives are financial contracts that Fannie Mae uses to hedge against interest rate fluctuations.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Armando Falcon Jr., head of OFHEO, commended the board's action and said, &quot;We are encouraged that the Board's announcement signals a new culture and a new direction for Fannie Mae.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>Finally, the Securities and Exchange Commission concluded that Fannie Mae, where Raines is chairman and chief executive, had engaged in questionable accounting practices over the past four years -- practices that Raines stubbornly defended even after serious questions had been raised.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="22,43"><scu uid="11" label="The SEC ruled that Fannie Mae violated accounting standards" weight="2"/><scu uid="11" label="The SEC ruled that Fannie Mae violated accounting standards" weight="2"/><scu uid="11" label="The SEC ruled that Fannie Mae violated accounting standards" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Malek, another Fannie audit committee member, joins Korologos at Aspen; he is an &quot;active trustee&quot; there.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>And who better to pontificate about ethics than a bunch of CEOs who lord over 10 million employees?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>Raines, whose senior management team has come under withering criticism by the company's main regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, testified to Congress two months ago that he expected to be held accountable by Fannie Mae's directors and shareholders if his interpretation of the accounting rules was set aside by the commission.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>But what will be Raines' lasting contribution?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Raines, who was chief executive and chairman, has been succeeded by two members of the company's board.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="37"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>Regulators in the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight ordered the company in September to boost its capital cushion, the amount of reserves it has to guard against financial losses, by some $5 billion (euro3.8 billion) by the middle of 2005.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Staff writers Jeffrey Birnbaum, Kathleen Day and Terence O'Hara contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>The September report raised a question about &quot;the overall safety and soundness of the enterprise,&quot; suggesting that a collapse is alarmingly conceivable.</line><line>Bosses at the federally chartered mortgage giant also formed their own opinion of what an accounting rule should say.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Fannie also considers Swygert to be independent.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Fannie Mae, is a government-sponsored private company and the largest source of funds for the U.S. mortgage market.</line><line>This would be like me as a taxpayer making up my own depreciation schedules to calculate deductions instead of using those prescribed by the government.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>The upheaval at Fannie Mae comes a year after similar problems at its smaller rival, McLean, Va.-based Freddie Mac, forced out two Freddie chief executives in rapid succession.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>In 2003, just the top five officers at Fannie Mae received $8.2 million (euro6.3 million) in cash bonuses.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Members of Congress and the Bush administration generally agree that the companies' primary regulator, OFHEO, is ill-equipped to oversee huge, complex institutions that could send shock waves through the economy and financial system if they ever foundered.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Regulators are now investigating the compensation awarded to Fannie's executives; Raines will receive an annual pension of more than $1 million under the terms of his exit.</line><line>The two presidential appointees on the committee at the time were Taylor C. Segue III, a lawyer in Michigan at Howard &amp; Howard; and William R. Harvey, president of Hampton University in Hampton, Va.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>The SEC and the Justice Department continue to examine those issues.</line><line>That agency concluded in September that company executives had manipulated expenses to smooth earnings and meet projected financial targets that would permit the executives to win maximum bonuses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>In this era, that should have been a fairly easy decision to make.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>The report said that Fannie Mae delayed booking $200 million of expenses in 1998, which allowed Raines and other top executives to receive millions of dollars in bonuses linked to Fannie's profit.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="16" label="OFHEO charged that Raines and other top executives received maximum bonuses of $27.1 million." weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>At a congressional hearing in October, Raines pointed to the SEC as the authority on accounting matters and pinned his hopes on a favorable decision from the agency.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Almost $400,000 of those grants went to the university during the years that Swygert was sitting on Fannie's board.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>You might end up like Fannie Mae CEO Franklin D. Raines.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="16,29,55,57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>In either case, with $9 billion in reported profit in jeopardy, he is now duty-bound to resign and take Chief Financial Officer Timothy Howard with him.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Contact him at alewisdenverpost.com.)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Fannie Mae also named another executive, Robert Levin, as its interim chief financial officer, to succeed J. Timothy Howard, who, like Raines, was forced out Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="3" label="On Dec. 21 Raines resigned" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>The vice chairwoman of the RAND Corp. board of trustees and former secretary of labor under President Ronald Reagan, Korologos must now oversee the investigation of Fannie Mae's accounting practices, governance and structure and executive compensation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>But they would also have to be committed to the company's affordable-housing goals, which are often identified with Democratic lawmakers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Raines, 55, is one of the most prominent African Americans in corporate America.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>Candidates would need significant credibility in a city that is dominated at both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue by Republicans, particularly as the company faces the virtually inevitable prospect of new legislation and tighter regulation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>So can someone please explain to me why Ernst &amp; Young is still Time Warner's auditor and why Hurst is still licensed to certify accounts of public companies?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>&quot;This board has all the classic hallmarks of a cozy, friendly board,&quot; Taxin, the institutional investors' adviser, said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>The costs of an all-out fight with a federal regulator would be too great, Fannie's board ultimately concluded, so Raines was told he would have to go.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Yes, indeed, said Greg Taxin, chief executive of Glass Lewis, an institutional advisory firm that advised Fannie shareholders to vote against all audit committee members up for re-election at Fannie Mae last year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Industry specialists say that Mudd and Ashley bring different skills to guide Fannie Mae through perhaps the most challenging period in its history.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Yet before the highly paid Raines was dodging his own accounting scandal, he was wagging a finger at others.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>The company is also expected to sell off part of its portfolio of mortgages and raise fresh capital by issuing stock.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>In a document delivered to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), Fannie Mae also acknowledged having received a letter from the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight (OFHEO), informing the company of its investigation into pay and bonuses of former chief executive Franklin Raines and of former finance director Timothy Howard, both of whom were sacked on December 21.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="7" sums="10,29,36,37,40,55,6"><scu uid="3" label="On Dec. 21 Raines resigned" weight="3"/><scu uid="3" label="On Dec. 21 Raines resigned" weight="3"/><scu uid="16" label="OFHEO charged that Raines and other top executives received maximum bonuses of $27.1 million." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Perhaps Raines believed Fannie Mae could hide in this complexity.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>He rose from a family that supplemented work with welfare to become a Rhodes scholar, president of the Harvard University Board of Overseers, director of the Office of Management and Budget under President Bill Clinton and a leader of the Washington business community.</line><line>Fannie Mae, for example, has debts to bondholders of $957 billion, equal to about a fifth of the publicly held portion of the U.S. national debt.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>The senior management of Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest buyer of mortgages, has come under increasing political and regulatory pressure after withering criticism from its main regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>The board's reluctance to defenestrate Raines and Howard, who appear to have misstated their company's financial statements to the tune of around $9 billion, fed suspicions that Fannie Mae's directors were loyal to management first, and shareholders second.</line><line>The Conservation Fund has received $54,000 from the Fannie Mae Foundation since 1995.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>With the mishandling of these accounting issues, one of those qualities has been seriously called into question.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Raines' successor must add billions of dollars to Fannie's reserves, which will be below the company's regulatory minimum when it records the additional losses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Since accounting woes surfaced at Fannie Mae, he argues that he relied on advice from Fannie Mae's auditor, KPMG, and adhered to Generally Accepted Accounting Principles, or GAAP.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>It wouldn't hold up in an audit.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>The announcement late Tuesday night came after a series of discussions over the last few days as board members debated Raines' future at Fannie Mae.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>But the issue that the SEC addressed last week is simple.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Fannie Mae has a lot of work ahead.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>It is altogether possible that Fannie Mae's board has acted entirely properly and in the shareholders' interests at all times.</line><line>But Korologos' other affiliations show links to Fannie Mae.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>A source with knowledge of the board's deliberations in recent days described a sometimes painful debate.</line><line>But Arne Christenson, a former Fannie Mae executive who was before that a top aide to then-Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich, said Raines will be difficult to replace.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>Jeffrey Sonnenfeld, an associate dean at the Yale School of Management, said of Mudd: &quot;He's a very strong, solid player.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>The directors of Fannie Mae, the big mortgage finance company, will meet Sunday to consider the fate of two senior executives who signed off on financial statements that violated accounting rules, people close to the company said Friday.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="11,14,25,41,43,44,51"><scu uid="11" label="The SEC ruled that Fannie Mae violated accounting standards" weight="2"/><scu uid="1" label="The directors of Fannie met on Dec. 19 to decide Raines' fate" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Two presidential appointees were on the audit committee at the end of 2003, but they are no longer associated with the company.</line><line>Segue did not return a phone call seeking comment and Harvey could not be reached.</line><line>She joined the board of Citigroup and said that she could not be a director at two financial services concerns simultaneously.</line><line>Since the company changed its guidelines in 2003, donations to charities with which directors are affiliated do not exceed $100,000 a year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>&quot;In this environment, it tends to put the CEO on the spot.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>He's basically been invisible at Fannie,&quot; said Bert Ely, a financial industry consultant who is a longtime critic of the company.</line><line>Mudd has provided leadership amid economic turmoil before, managing GE Capital's Asia-Pacific division through the Asian financial crisis in the late 1990s.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>While the audit committee members had an obligation to monitor Fannie's accounting, they are not the only directors bearing responsibility for the debacle at the company.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Some corporate governance specialists were stunned by allegations that Fannie engaged in accounting manipulations years after the watershed scandals at Enron Corp. and WorldCom Inc. Those debacles inspired tough new legal penalties for accounting manipulations, served a warning to corporate bosses and seemed to bring about a change in the culture of America's boardrooms.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>&quot;The CEOs of the Business Roundtable are aiming to make a lasting contribution to business ethics and the way our companies are run,&quot; Raines said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>We've all been pondering the Kerik question: How did President Bush's serially flawed Homeland Security Department nominee imagine he could survive the confirmation process?</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>At Fannie Mae, Raines seemed to understand the stakes back in October when he told a House committee he had checked and rechecked his firm's accounting and would take personal responsibility for it.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="42"><scu uid="19" label="Raines said he expected to be held accountable if his interpretation of the accounting rules was not accepted" weight="1"/><scu uid="19" label="Raines said he expected to be held accountable if his interpretation of the accounting rules was not accepted" weight="1"/><scu uid="19" label="Raines said he expected to be held accountable if his interpretation of the accounting rules was not accepted" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>Fannie Mae, embroiled in an accounting scandal, now faces rising suspicions about pay and benefits for its former directors.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Raines, the source said, at times argued passionately that he had done nothing wrong.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>But high tech's highhandedness has nothing on the leadership at Fannie Mae.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>They appear to have done so only under duress from Fannie's chief regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, which in September put the company on notice that its improper accounting had vastly overstated profits and misrepresented its financial position.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="13,35"><scu uid="26" label="OFHEO demanded significant changes in senior management." weight="1"/><scu uid="14" label="OFHEO report charged that Fannie Mae violated accounting rules." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Though it was not apparent at the time, Raines's downfall began in early 2003, when Freddie Mac disclosed that it had made billions of dollars of accounting errors.</line><line>Raines' departure was structured as an early retirement.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>In October, Raines went before Congress and denied the accusation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>She was the institute's chairwoman for the first four of those years.</line><line>A spokesman for Xerox did not return a request for comment from Mulcahy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>The area in which Fannie Mae misstated earnings -- derivatives -- is exceedingly complex.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>On Capitol Hill, the scandal at Fannie Mae has reinvigorated efforts to create a more powerful regulator for Fannie and Freddie.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>He is a partner with Raines in the Washington Baseball Club, which is bringing the Montreal Expos to the nation's capital.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Ann McLaughlin Korologos, the presiding non-management director, thanked Raines and Howard for their &quot;many contributions&quot; and said the board &quot;takes these steps today to move the company forward.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>With a new year approaching, it seems a perfect time for the Fannie board to look hard and long at its own roles in the mess.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>Mortgage giant Fannie Mae announced Friday it was withholding millions of dollars in bonuses from its top executives as it continued to come to grips with revelations of serious financial reporting problems.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="0,3"><scu uid="10" label="Raines would be denied the cash bonus for 2004" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>It came after the company's main regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, demanded significant changes to the company's senior management and threatened to declare that Fannie Mae had failed to meet its capital requirements, people close to the process said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>Zoellick has also been said to be on the short list of contenders to be the next head of the World Bank.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>What he lacks, however, are the strong political connections that made Raines such a powerful force on Capitol Hill.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>She is chairwoman emeritus of the Aspen Institute, a nonprofit group in Washington that has received $280,000 in grants from the Fannie Mae Foundation, a nonprofit arm that works for affordable housing, between 1996 and 2002.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Then in January, Raines brought The Business Roundtable Institute for Corporate Ethics to the University of Virginia.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>First, the D.C. Council managed to unravel a carefully negotiated deal to bring Major League Baseball back to Washington, which Raines, as a leading member of the would-be local ownership group, has been working on for years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>Long a formidable political power in Washington, Fannie Mae's support has eroded in recent months both because of the conclusions of regulators and because of the growing effectiveness of rival financial institutions.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>&quot;I'm sure he (Raines) would have preferred to have stayed, but things are the way they are,&quot; said attorney R. Timothy Columbus, a close friend of Raines.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>In a letter on Sept. 20, Armando Falcon Jr., the director of the oversight office, told Fannie Mae directors that the agency had found significant evidence that raised &quot;doubts concerning the validity of previously reported financial results, the adequacy of regulatory capital, the quality of management supervision and the overall safety and soundness of the enterprise.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>Raines was also a member of the Time Warner audit committee when those practices were vigorously defended after being exposed by my intrepid colleague, Alec Klein, in The Washington Post.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>&quot;He's what I call the chief inside guy -- the guy who makes things run every day.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Take Ann Korologos.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>According to Monday's Wall Street Journal, Raines privately makes the case that he did nothing at Fannie Mae that warrants his dismissal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>Considering that all this was happening in the wake of the unfolding Enron scandal, the answer was pretty clear.</line><line>Moreover, as Fannie directors resume their urgent discussions this weekend, they need to move quickly to replace KPMG as the company's auditor for having provided them with bad advice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>In its new SEC filing on Friday, Fannie Mae did not disclose the total amount in cash bonuses that were being eliminated, and company spokesmen also refused to give a figure other than to indicate it would be in the millions of dollars and would affect the company's 43 top executives.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>Let's give the directors at Time Warner and AOL the benefit of the doubt and assume that they knew nothing about the true nature of the transactions with PurchasePro when a reporter from The Washington Post showed up with documents suggesting they were a sham.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>And since 1989, the Fannie Mae Foundation has dispensed 35 grants to Howard University, totaling $555,186.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Franklin Raines stepped down Tuesday as chairman and chief executive of Fannie Mae, as the company's directors ended days of tense and emotional deliberations and bowed to pressure from regulators who wanted him out.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,12,25,42,51,55"><scu uid="3" label="On Dec. 21 Raines resigned" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Here's what he told Congress about Enron in 2002: &quot;It is wholly irresponsible and unacceptable for corporate leaders to say they did not know... about the operations and activities of their company, particularly when it comes to risks that threaten the fundamental viability of their company.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>But its announcement was held up, as directors continued to discuss different scenarios in which Raines would remain chief executive, including the appointment of an independent chairman.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>Fannie's top managers looked at the federal rule on accounting for futures, swaps and other such financial instruments, and they decided they didn't agree with it.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>He has worked at Fannie Mae twice before, including one stint in the 1990s when he was a senior executive in charge of its affordable-housing business as well as its legal affairs and governmental relations offices.</line><line>Fannie Mae said in November that a restatement would force it to recognize $9 billion in losses over the last three and a half years, wiping out more than a third of its profits over that period.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Mulcahy left Fannie's board last September, a few days before OFHEO's devastating report was made public.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>They did this not merely before the rule in question went into effect -- but afterward.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>But the appearance of conflicts still resonates, especially in its lumbering approach to ousting Raines and Howard.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>The Washington D.C.-based housing finance company, which stands behind or owns a quarter of the nation's mortgages, faces a criminal investigation by the Justice Department; a civil investigation by the Securities and Exchange Commission; an ongoing probe of other accounting issues by its main regulator, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight; and class-action lawsuits by investors.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="32,5"><scu uid="21" label="The company still faced a Justice Department criminal investigation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>Tough consequences will follow: The Justice Department is pursuing a criminal investigation; the SEC is pursuing a civil one; the House promises hearings; and class-action lawsuits are in the works.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="1" sums="10"><scu uid="21" label="The company still faced a Justice Department criminal investigation" weight="2"/><scu uid="22" label="The company still faced an SEC civil investigation. " weight="1"/><scu uid="22" label="The company still faced an SEC civil investigation. " weight="1"/><scu uid="24" label="The company still faced several class-action lawsuits." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>Raines, who led the Office of Management and Budget at the White House under President Bill Clinton, has lately appeared to have lost much of the support he had from Republicans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>If you are responsible for massive amounts of accounting, maybe it's not a good idea to criticize someone else's accounting.</line><line>Yet Raines signed off on the books and defended the methods.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>A Fannie Mae spokesman said that none of the company's directors were available to comment for this article.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>Now, two years and many subpoenas later, it turns out that Klein was right and Time Warner shareholders are out $500 million.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>You don't want any ambiguity as to what is known and what is not known.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>A Fannie spokesman said the company's criteria for independence were far stricter than those of the New York Stock Exchange.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>Raines has denied that the expenses were manipulated for such purposes.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>And H. Patrick Swygert, the president of Howard University and a Fannie director since 2000, also has ties to the Federal City Council.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041218.0026"><line>As it has in recent days, the company again Friday declined to issue a statement from the directors about how it intended to proceed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>But the agency suffered a major setback on Wednesday when the SEC's chief accountant said that the company had violated accounting rules on its treatment of investments in derivatives and in the way it accounted for losses from prepaid loans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0028"><line>In the baseball matter, of course, Raines is as much a victim of the District's political bumbling as the rest of us. But what's baffling about the two accounting imbroglios is how Raines and so many other smart executives and professionals could have been so stupid.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>Hmmm.</line><line>Korologos has also been a visiting fellow at the Urban Institute, which has received $2.65 million in grants from the Fannie Mae Foundation since 1990, and she sits on the corporate council of the Conservation Fund, a nonprofit group that works to protect the nation's land and water resources.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041221.0314"><line>A former president of the Mortgage Bankers Association, a trade group, he testified in front of a Congressional Housing Subcommittee in 1991 in support of Fannie Mae.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050121.1177"><line>This action will affect 43 top officials who will lose millions of dollars in scheduled performance bonuses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>The entire board should don a hair shirt.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>Howard, 56, who joined Fannie Mae in 1982 and served as chief financial officer since 1990, oversaw Fannie's accounting.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="49,57"/></line><line>Sources said the regulator was determined to initiate a public proceeding to remove Raines if the board did not act.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>Raines can claim 600,000 dollars in salary for the period from December 22 to June 22, 2005, the date at which his retirement becomes effective, the Fannie Mae document shows.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>Accounting for them involves assumptions and predictions -- a thick realm of grey.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>&quot;The point of that committee is to protect shareholders from precisely what happened here,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041221.0154"><line>In addition, the company guarantees principal and interest payments on $1.9 trillion of mortgage-backed securities.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>Following the departure of Raines and Howard, vice-president Daniel Mudd was named interim chief executive while executive vice-president Robert Levin was promoted to finance director, the company said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041219.0114"><line>The company said previously that any requirement that it restate its earnings could lead it to declare about $9 billion in losses, wiping out more than a third of its earnings over the period.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>But Fannie's chief executive, Franklin Raines, continued to raise the complexity defense, saying the accounting weaknesses identified in the report were a matter of interpretation.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="20,22"><scu uid="25" label="Raines denied wrongdoing." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041228.0460"><line>Raines' monthly pension payments should then amount to 116,300 dollars.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041217.0010"><line>Fannie Mae's behavior raises the same question: How did its managers believe they could get away with this?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041220.0176"><line>During this period, Raines made $14 million in salary and bonus, plus $25.6 million in incentive pay.</line><line>(Al Lewis is a columnist for The Denver Post.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041224.0170"><line>As of last year, they included Thomas P. Gerrity, the chairman and a former dean of the Wharton School at the University of Pennsylvania; Frederic V. Malek, the chairman of Thayer Capital Partners, a private equity firm; Anne M. Mulcahy, the chief executive of Xerox; and Joe K. Pickett, the retired chief executive of HomeSide International, parent of a mortgage lending company.</line></document></collection>